{
  "Nuclear fission is the process of:": "",
  "Splitting a heavy nucleus into smaller nuclei": "",
  "Removing electrons from an atom": "",
  "Combining light nuclei into a heavier one": "",
  "Adding neutrons to a stable nucleus": "",
  "Nuclear fission splits a heavy nucleus (like uranium-235) into lighter nuclei, releasing neutrons and energy. A chain reaction occurs when released neutrons trigger more fissions. The answer is 'Splitting a heavy nucleus into smaller nuclei'. The other options describe different processes: combining nuclei is fusion, removing electrons is ionization, and adding neutrons alone is neutron capture.": "",
  "Nuclear fusion is the process of:": "",
  "Combining light nuclei into a heavier nucleus": "",
  "Breaking chemical bonds between atoms": "",
  "Ionizing atoms by removing electrons": "",
  "Splitting heavy nuclei into lighter ones": "",
  "Nuclear fusion combines light nuclei (like hydrogen) into heavier ones, releasing energy. It requires extremely high temperatures (millions of degrees) to overcome electrostatic repulsion. The answer is 'Combining light nuclei into a heavier nucleus'. Splitting heavy nuclei describes fission, not fusion.": "",
  "The sun produces energy through:": "",
  "Nuclear fusion of hydrogen nuclei": "",
  "Chemical combustion of gases": "",
  "Nuclear fission of uranium atoms": "",
  "Radioactive decay of heavy elements": "",
  "The sun produces energy by fusing hydrogen nuclei into helium at extremely high temperatures and pressures. This fusion process releases enormous amounts of energy. The answer is 'Nuclear fusion of hydrogen nuclei'. The sun does not use fission, combustion, or simple radioactive decay to generate its energy.": "",
  "Nuclear power plants use:": "",
  "Fission of uranium-235 to generate heat": "",
  "Solar energy to produce electricity": "",
  "Fusion of hydrogen to boil water": "",
  "Combustion of coal to spin turbines": "",
  "Nuclear power plants generate electricity by using the fission of uranium-235 to produce heat, which boils water and drives steam turbines. Fusion is not yet used commercially for power generation.": "",
  "Fusion requires extremely high:": "",
  "Numbers of atoms to begin": "",
  "Temperatures (millions of degrees)": "",
  "Pressures only, not temperatures": "",
  "Volumes of gas to sustain itself": "",
  "Nuclear fusion requires extremely high temperatures (millions of degrees) to overcome the electrostatic repulsion between positively charged nuclei. This is why fusion is difficult to achieve on Earth but occurs naturally in stars.": "",
  "The mass defect in nuclear reactions represents:": "",
  "Protons gained during the reaction": "",
  "Matter that has been completely destroyed": "",
  "Mass converted to energy (E = mc²)": "",
  "Neutrons lost from the nucleus": "",
  "The mass defect is the difference between the mass of the nucleus and the sum of its individual protons and neutrons. This missing mass is converted to energy via Einstein's equation E = mc². Matter is not destroyed but transformed into energy.": "",
  "Which process releases more energy per unit mass?": "",
  "Both release equal amounts of energy": "",
  "Chemical combustion releases the most": "",
  "Fission releases the most energy": "",
  "Fusion releases the most energy": "",
  "Nuclear fusion releases more energy per unit mass than fission or chemical combustion. This is because the binding energy per nucleon increases most dramatically when light nuclei fuse together. However, achieving the extreme conditions needed for fusion remains a major engineering challenge.": "",
  "In a fission chain reaction, what particles are released that trigger additional fission events?": "",
  "Electrons are released to trigger more events": "",
  "Neutrons are released to trigger more fission": "",
  "Protons are released to trigger more events": "",
  "Alpha particles are released to trigger more events": "",
  "In a fission chain reaction, neutrons released from one fission event strike other heavy nuclei, causing them to split as well. This self-sustaining process is what makes nuclear reactors and nuclear weapons possible.": "",
  "Which isotope is most commonly used as fuel in nuclear fission reactors?": "",
  "Carbon-14 is most commonly used": "",
  "Hydrogen-2 is most commonly used": "",
  "Uranium-235 is most commonly used": "",
  "Helium-4 is most commonly used": "",
  "Uranium-235 is the most commonly used fuel in nuclear fission reactors because it readily undergoes fission when struck by a neutron. Carbon-14 is used in dating, hydrogen-2 (deuterium) is relevant to fusion, and helium-4 is a product of fusion.": "",
  "What is the role of control rods in a nuclear fission reactor?": "",
  "They provide additional fuel for the reaction": "",
  "They speed up the chain reaction process": "",
  "They convert heat energy into electricity": "",
  "They absorb neutrons to regulate the chain reaction": "",
  "Control rods are made of materials like boron or cadmium that absorb neutrons. By inserting or withdrawing them, operators can slow down or speed up the fission chain reaction, keeping the reactor running safely and at a controlled rate.": "",
  "What is nuclear fission?": "",
  "The splitting of a heavy atomic nucleus into two or more lighter nuclei with energy release": "",
  "The joining of two light atomic nuclei into one heavier nucleus with energy release": "",
  "The removal of electrons from atoms through the application of electrical energy": "",
  "The absorption of gamma radiation by a nucleus causing it to become more stable": "",
  "Nuclear fission is defined as the splitting of a heavy atomic nucleus (such as uranium-235 or plutonium-239) into two or more lighter nuclei, along with the release of neutrons and a large amount of energy. This process is the basis for nuclear power and nuclear weapons.": "",
  "What is nuclear fusion?": "",
  "The breakdown of unstable atoms through the emission of radioactive particles over time": "",
  "The combining of two light nuclei to form a heavier nucleus with energy release": "",
  "The splitting of a heavy nucleus into lighter fragments when struck by neutrons": "",
  "The conversion of chemical energy into nuclear energy through heating compounds": "",
  "Nuclear fusion is defined as the process in which two light nuclei (such as hydrogen isotopes) combine to form a heavier nucleus, releasing a tremendous amount of energy. Fusion is the process that powers stars, including our sun.": "",
  "Define the term 'mass defect' in nuclear chemistry.": "",
  "The total mass of all protons and neutrons added together in a nucleus": "",
  "The number of neutrons lost during a radioactive decay process event": "",
  "The difference between the total mass of individual nucleons and the actual mass of the nucleus": "",
  "The increase in mass that occurs when two atoms undergo a chemical bonding reaction": "",
  "The mass defect is the difference between the sum of the masses of the individual protons and neutrons and the actual measured mass of the nucleus. This 'missing' mass has been converted into binding energy that holds the nucleus together, as described by E = mc².": "",
  "What is a chain reaction in nuclear fission?": "",
  "A reaction where products are continuously removed to prevent further splitting": "",
  "A reaction where only one nucleus splits and then the process immediately stops": "",
  "A reaction where fission products combine back together to reform the original atom": "",
  "A self-sustaining reaction where neutrons from one fission trigger additional fissions": "",
  "A chain reaction occurs when neutrons released from one fission event strike other fissile nuclei, causing them to split and release more neutrons. This process repeats continuously, making the reaction self-sustaining. Control rods are used in reactors to manage this process.": "",
  "What is meant by 'critical mass' in nuclear physics?": "",
  "The minimum amount of fissile material needed to sustain a chain reaction": "",
  "The maximum temperature required to start a nuclear fusion reaction process": "",
  "The total weight of all radioactive waste produced by a nuclear power plant": "",
  "The amount of energy released when a single uranium atom undergoes fission": "",
  "Critical mass is the minimum amount of fissile material (such as uranium-235) needed to sustain a nuclear chain reaction. Below this amount, too many neutrons escape without causing further fission, and the reaction dies out.": "",
  "Define 'binding energy' in the context of an atomic nucleus.": "",
  "The energy needed to remove an electron from the outermost shell of an atom": "",
  "The energy required to completely separate a nucleus into its individual protons and neutrons": "",
  "The energy released when a chemical bond forms between two different atoms": "",
  "The energy stored in the electrons that orbit around the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "Nuclear binding energy is the energy required to disassemble a nucleus into its separate protons and neutrons. It is also the energy that was released when the nucleus formed. The greater the binding energy per nucleon, the more stable the nucleus.": "",
  "What does Einstein's equation E = mc² describe in nuclear reactions?": "",
  "It calculates the speed of neutrons released during a fission chain reaction": "",
  "It determines the half-life of a radioactive isotope based on its atomic mass": "",
  "It shows that mass and energy are interchangeable, with a small mass producing enormous energy": "",
  "It measures the temperature required to initiate a nuclear fusion reaction event": "",
  "Einstein's equation E = mc² shows the equivalence of mass and energy. In nuclear reactions, a small amount of mass (the mass defect) is converted into a very large amount of energy because the speed of light squared (c²) is an enormous number.": "",
  "What is the term for the process in which hydrogen nuclei combine to form helium inside stars?": "",
  "The process is called radioactive decay of hydrogen atoms": "",
  "The process is called chemical combustion of hydrogen gas": "",
  "The process is called nuclear fission of hydrogen nuclei": "",
  "The process is called nuclear fusion or stellar nucleosynthesis": "",
  "The process of hydrogen nuclei combining to form helium inside stars is called nuclear fusion (or stellar nucleosynthesis). The extreme temperatures and pressures in a star's core provide the conditions needed to overcome the electrostatic repulsion between nuclei.": "",
  "What is a 'fissile' material?": "",
  "Any material that can absorb neutrons without undergoing any nuclear reaction": "",
  "A material whose nucleus can undergo fission when struck by a neutron": "",
  "A material that only undergoes fusion at extremely high temperatures in stars": "",
  "Any element that is found naturally in a radioactive form on Earth today": "",
  "A fissile material is one whose atomic nuclei can undergo fission when struck by a neutron. Common examples include uranium-235 and plutonium-239. Not all radioactive materials are fissile — fissile specifically means they can sustain a fission chain reaction.": "",
  "What does 'electrostatic repulsion' refer to in the context of nuclear fusion?": "",
  "The attraction between neutrons and protons inside an atomic nucleus": "",
  "The force that pushes positively charged nuclei apart and must be overcome for fusion": "",
  "The energy released when two nuclei successfully combine during a fusion event": "",
  "The magnetic field generated inside a nuclear reactor during normal fission operations": "",
  "Electrostatic repulsion is the force that pushes positively charged nuclei apart (like charges repel). For fusion to occur, nuclei must be brought close enough for the strong nuclear force to take over, which requires extremely high temperatures to overcome this repulsion.": "",
  "A scientist working at a research facility wants to create energy the same way the sun does. What process would they need to replicate?": "",
  "They would need to split uranium atoms in a controlled fission reactor": "",
  "They would need to burn hydrogen gas at very high temperatures in a furnace": "",
  "They would need to fuse hydrogen nuclei at extremely high temperatures and pressures": "",
  "They would need to allow radioactive materials to naturally decay over long periods": "",
  "The sun produces energy through nuclear fusion, where hydrogen nuclei combine to form helium. To replicate this, scientists would need to achieve the extreme temperatures (millions of degrees) and pressures necessary to overcome electrostatic repulsion between nuclei.": "",
  "A nuclear power plant operator notices the reactor is producing too much heat. What should they do with the control rods?": "",
  "Remove the control rods completely to allow better cooling of the reactor core": "",
  "Replace the control rods with fresh uranium fuel rods to balance the temperature": "",
  "Keep the control rods in the same position since temperature changes are normal": "",
  "Insert the control rods further to absorb more neutrons and slow the chain reaction": "",
  "Control rods absorb neutrons, which slows or stops the fission chain reaction. By inserting them further into the reactor core, the operator reduces the number of neutrons available to cause fission, lowering the heat output. Removing them would have the opposite, dangerous effect.": "",
  "A student measures the mass of the products of a nuclear reaction and finds they weigh slightly less than the original reactants. What happened to the missing mass?": "",
  "The missing mass evaporated into the surrounding air during the reaction process": "",
  "The missing mass was converted into energy according to the equation E = mc²": "",
  "The missing mass was absorbed by the container holding the nuclear reaction materials": "",
  "The missing mass was an error in measurement since mass is always perfectly conserved": "",
  "In nuclear reactions, the small amount of mass that appears to be 'missing' (the mass defect) has been converted into energy. Einstein's equation E = mc² explains this: even a tiny amount of mass converts into an enormous amount of energy because it is multiplied by the speed of light squared.": "",
  "An engineer is comparing energy sources for a new power plant. Why might they choose nuclear fission over coal combustion?": "",
  "Coal combustion produces no waste products while fission creates minimal waste": "",
  "Nuclear fission releases no greenhouse gases during operation and produces far more energy per kilogram of fuel": "",
  "Coal combustion requires more safety precautions than nuclear fission during daily use": "",
  "Nuclear fission uses a simpler technology that costs less to build and operate overall": "",
  "Nuclear fission produces vastly more energy per kilogram of fuel than coal and does not emit greenhouse gases during operation. While nuclear plants have their own challenges (radioactive waste, high construction costs), the energy density and lack of carbon emissions are significant advantages.": "",
  "In a lab demonstration, a teacher explains that a tiny amount of mass can produce a huge amount of energy. Which concept best explains this?": "",
  "The law of conservation of mass states that mass cannot be created or destroyed": "",
  "The concept of specific heat explains how materials absorb different amounts of energy": "",
  "Einstein's mass-energy equivalence (E = mc²) shows mass converts to enormous energy": "",
  "The kinetic molecular theory explains how particles move faster at higher temperatures": "",
  "Einstein's equation E = mc² explains why a small mass produces enormous energy. The speed of light (c) is approximately 3 x 10⁸ m/s, so c² is about 9 x 10¹⁶. Even a tiny mass multiplied by this enormous number yields a huge amount of energy.": "",
  "A student reads that scientists are trying to build fusion reactors on Earth but face enormous challenges. What is the main difficulty?": "",
  "There is not enough hydrogen on Earth to use as fuel for a fusion reactor": "",
  "Fusion reactions produce too much radioactive waste to be practical for energy use": "",
  "Fusion produces less energy than fission so it is not worth the investment": "",
  "Achieving and sustaining the extreme temperatures needed to overcome electrostatic repulsion is very difficult": "",
  "The main challenge of fusion on Earth is achieving and containing the extreme temperatures (over 100 million degrees) needed to overcome electrostatic repulsion between nuclei. No ordinary container can hold such hot plasma, so scientists use magnetic confinement or lasers.": "",
  "A news report states that a nuclear submarine can operate for years without refueling. What explains this capability?": "",
  "Nuclear fission releases millions of times more energy per kilogram than chemical fuels": "",
  "Submarines use solar panels on their hull to supplement their nuclear fuel supply": "",
  "The submarine converts seawater directly into nuclear fuel during its normal voyage": "",
  "Nuclear submarines actually need to refuel every few months just like diesel submarines": "",
  "Nuclear fission releases millions of times more energy per kilogram of fuel than chemical combustion. This enormous energy density means a nuclear submarine can carry a small amount of uranium fuel and operate for many years before needing to refuel.": "",
  "A student notices that the total mass of a helium-4 nucleus is less than the combined mass of 2 separate protons and 2 separate neutrons. What accounts for this difference?": "",
  "Some protons were destroyed when the nucleus formed, reducing the total mass": "",
  "The mass defect was converted into nuclear binding energy that holds the nucleus together": "",
  "The measurement equipment was inaccurate since mass must always be perfectly conserved": "",
  "The neutrons inside the nucleus weigh less than free neutrons because of nuclear pressure": "",
  "The mass defect — the difference between the mass of individual nucleons and the assembled nucleus — is converted into binding energy via E = mc². This binding energy is what holds the protons and neutrons together in the nucleus. The stronger the binding energy per nucleon, the more stable the nucleus.": "",
  "During a class discussion, a student asks why we cannot simply use fusion power plants instead of fission plants. Which response is most accurate?": "",
  "Fusion has already replaced fission in most countries but the student has not heard about it": "",
  "Fusion produces far less energy than fission so it would not be practical for power plants": "",
  "We have not yet developed technology to sustain and contain fusion reactions for continuous power": "",
  "Fusion fuel is extremely rare on Earth making it impossible to supply a power plant": "",
  "While fusion produces more energy per unit mass than fission and uses abundant hydrogen fuel, we have not yet developed the technology to sustain and contain fusion reactions long enough to generate continuous electricity. The extreme temperatures and containment challenges remain unsolved for practical power generation.": "",
  "A researcher finds that 1 kg of uranium fuel in a fission reactor produces as much energy as burning about 3 million kg of coal. What principle explains this dramatic difference?": "",
  "Coal burns inefficiently because most of its mass is water that does not contribute energy": "",
  "Uranium is denser than coal so it naturally contains more stored chemical bond energy": "",
  "Coal only releases thermal energy while uranium releases both thermal and electrical energy": "",
  "Nuclear reactions convert mass to energy (E = mc²), which releases far more energy than breaking chemical bonds": "",
  "Nuclear fission converts a small amount of mass into energy via E = mc², releasing millions of times more energy per kilogram than chemical reactions like burning coal. Chemical combustion only rearranges electrons in bonds, while nuclear reactions alter the nucleus itself, tapping into the much stronger nuclear forces.": ""
